Introduction

Each year, thousands of dogs are adopted from shelters, but not all adoptions are permanent. Some dogs are returned due to destructive behaviors, disobedience, or adopter preparedness. Instead, in this project, we will use machine learning to predict whether a dog will be returned based solely on a dog's characteristics.

By doing this project, it could help shelters make more informed adoption recommendations and improve long-term placement outcomes. Identifying the traits that lead to unsuccessful adoptions can help shelters proactively work on addressing behavioral issues and match dogs to more suitable homes. Overall, this can help reduce stress in the animals involved as well as reduce euthanasia rates in shelters.

The data set will we will use is from Bloomington Animal Shelter based in Indiana. We will apply decision tree algorithms due to their ability to handle categorical features like breed.

This dataset contains detailed information about the outcomes of animals adopted from the Bloomington Animal Shelter

The table is originally sorted by "id" which is unique for each specific animal

The columns include:
intakedate: Date of admission to the shelter. (Date)
intakereason: Reason for admission to the shelter. (String)
istransfer: Whether the animal was transferred from another shelter. (Boolean)
sheltercode: Unique code assigned to the animal. (String)
animalname: Name of the animal. (String)
breedname: Breed of the animal. (String)
basecolour: Color of the animal. (String)
speciesname: Species of the animal. (String)
animalage: Age of the animal. (Integer)
sexname: Sex of the animal. (String)
location: Location of the animal. (String)
movementdate: Date of movement. (Date)
movementtype: Type of movement. (String)
istrial: Whether the animal was on trial. (Boolean)
returndate: Date of return. (Date)
returnedreason: Reason for return. (String)
deceaseddate: Date of death. (Date)
deceasedreason: Reason for death. (String)
diedoffshelter: Whether the animal died offsite. (Boolean)
puttosleep: Whether the animal was euthanized. (Boolean)

We are only checking whether an animal was returned at least once to the shelter, so we just have to check the first row of each individual animal. If the first row is false, then the animal was adopted and never returned to the shelter. If the first row is true, then the animal was returned at least once to the shelter. It may have been adopted or returned some number of times after that, but for this analysis, we only care if it was returned one time.

In[100]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

contingency = pd.crosstab(processed_df['breedname'], processed_df['has_been_returned'])
contingency['return_rate'] = contingency[True] / (contingency[True] + contingency[False])
contingency = contingency[(contingency[True] + contingency[False]) >= 5]
top_10_returns = contingency.sort_values(by='return_rate', ascending=False).head(10)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
top_10_returns['return_rate'].plot(kind='barh', color='pink', edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Return Rate')
plt.ylabel('Breed')
plt.title('Top 10 Dog Breeds with Highest Return Rates')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()  # So highest return rate is at top
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The p-value given by the chi squared test is smaller than our signifance value of 0.05, thus we reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis. This means that the probability of seeing this result with the null hypothesis being true is extremely unlikely. Thus, we can conclude that the breed does influence the return rate of an animal.

Second Relationship

Null Hypothesis: The mean time spent in shelter is equal across all intake reasons.

Alternative Hypothesis: At least one intake reason group has a significantly different mean time in shelter.

We'll use an ANOVA test because we want to compare the means of the shelter times of 3 or more groups. Before we proceed, we must ensure we are working with normal distributions.

In[103]:

We can observe that most of the data is skewed, so we will use the Kruskal-Wallis test, an extension of the ANOVA test that compares the medians instead of the means.

For this test, we'll use an alpha-value of 0.05

In[104]:
from scipy.stats import kruskal

groups = []
unique_reasons = dogs_df['intakereason'].unique()

for reason in unique_reasons:
    group_data = dogs_df[dogs_df['intakereason'] == reason]['days_in_shelter'].dropna().values
    groups.append(group_data)

h_stat, p_value = kruskal(*groups)
print(f"H-statistic = {h_stat}, p-value = {p_value}")

H-statistic = 245.8431899144991, p-value = 2.8027125597278104e-40

After performing the Kruskal-Wallis, test we got a p-value of 1.831915312762992e-40. This is less than our alpha-value of 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis. This means there is at least one intake reason group's median that is different from another group.

We're not done yet, we will now do a post-hoc test to determine which group(s) is different. We'll do Dunn's test, which is a post-hoc test often used after the Kruskal-Wallis test, and we'll also use it with Bonferroni's Correction.

In[105]:
!pip install scikit-posthocs
import scikit_posthocs as sp

dunn_results = sp.posthoc_dunn(
    dogs_df,
    val_col='days_in_shelter',
    group_col='intakereason',
    p_adjust='bonferroni'  # adjust for multiple comparisons
)

sig_matrix = dunn_results < 0.05

sig_pairs = []
for i in range(len(sig_matrix)):
    for j in range(i+1, len(sig_matrix)):
        if sig_matrix.iloc[i,j]:
            group1 = sig_matrix.columns[i]
            group2 = sig_matrix.columns[j]
            p_value = dunn_results.iloc[i,j]
            sig_pairs.append((group1, group2, p_value))

# Sort by most significant
sig_pairs_sorted = sorted(sig_pairs, key=lambda x: x[2])
for pair in sig_pairs_sorted:
    print(f"{pair[0]} vs {pair[1]}: p = {pair[2]}")

Third Relationship

Another hypothesis we can test is if age has on the reason for adoption for a pet. For example, does an older pet mean that it will be more likely to be abandonded? \ H0: The mean age of any adopted pet is the same as the mean of an abandoned pet. \ HA: The mean age of any adopted pet is different than the mean of an abandoned pet.

In[107]:
#Create a new df for our analysis
age_df = df

#create a function to make doing analysis with age a little bit easier, changes animal age entries into decimal year entries
def x(n):
    parts = n.split()

    if ("year" in parts or "years" in parts):
        years = int(parts[0])
        months = int(parts[2]) if "months." in parts or "month." in parts else 0
        return round(years + (months / 12), 2)

    elif ("week." in parts or "weeks." in parts):
        weeks = int(parts[0])
        return round(weeks / 52, 2)

    return None

# Apply function to create new 'Age' column
age_df['Age'] = age_df['animalage'].apply(x)
age_df

Primary Analysis

Our question is a classification problem. We are using the input variables of color, breed, and age to classify an adopted dog into one of two possible categories: returned to the shelter or never returned to the shelter. Thus, we looked at different models for classification problems such as decision, random forest, and logistic regression.

We decided to utilize random to classify whether an animal would be returned to the shelter. This was mainly because our dependent variable, or ultimate outcome, is a binary yes/no answer, which can fits the output from a random forest. We also liked that random forest models are able to gain higher accuracy scores, due to the combination of several models that reduces overall variance. Random forest is also resistant to overfitting as the different base models are trained on different subsections of the data.

In order to utilize the random forest classification, we had to transform our categorical variables, color and breed, into a vector using one-hot encoding.

Model Creation

We used the sklearn library to create a random forest classifier for predicting whether an adopted animal will be returned or not. After adding all appropriate import statements, we preprocessed the data to be a better input for the model.

First, we created a new column "returned" to indicate whether an animal was returned to the shelter, based on whether a date is present in the returndate column.

We then split the variable into training features (age, color, and breed) and the target variable (returned).

We use the train_test_split method to randomly split the data.

Next, we use a transformer pipeline with a oneHotEncoder to change the categorical variables breed and color into numerical data for the model.

In[108]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Step 1: Specify what variables are to be used in estimation
age_df['returned'] = age_df['returndate'].notna()
null = age_df.isna().sum()
print(null)
model_df = age_df[['breedname', 'Age', 'basecolour', 'returned']].copy()
temp = model_df['Age'].mean()
model_df['Age'] = model_df['Age'].fillna(temp)

# Step 2: Split into features and target variables
x = model_df[['breedname', 'Age', 'basecolour']]
y = model_df['returned'].astype(int)

# Step 3: Split data into seperate sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(x, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Step 4: Split the features
categorical_features = ['breedname', 'basecolour']
numeric_features = ['Age']

# Step 5: Process features
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('encoding', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'), categorical_features)
    ],
    remainder='passthrough'
)

# Step 6: Create pipeline
model_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('preprocessing', preprocessor),
    # ('classifier', LogisticRegression(max_iter=100))
    # ('classifier', KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5))
    # ('classifier', DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=42))
    ('classifier', RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42))
])

# # Step 7: Fit the model
model_pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

from collections import defaultdict

encoded_feature_names = list(ohe.get_feature_names_out(categorical_features))
feature_names = encoded_feature_names + numeric_features
importances = model_pipeline.named_steps['classifier'].feature_importances_

feature_group_map = defaultdict(list)
for name, importance in zip(feature_names, importances):
    if name.startswith('breedname_'):
        feature_group_map['breedname'].append(importance)
    elif name.startswith('basecolour_'):
        feature_group_map['basecolour'].append(importance)
    elif name == 'Age':
        feature_group_map['Age'].append(importance)

grouped_importance = {feature: sum(importances) for feature, importances in feature_group_map.items()}

grouped_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(grouped_importance, orient='index', columns=['Importance'])
grouped_df = grouped_df.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)


plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

An uninformed reader would certainly learn more about animal shelters, data cleaning, and machine learning, specifically Decision Trees. We have laid out our purpose, significance, and methology clearly, explaining what we are doing and why for each step in the data cleaning and model creation elemnents of our project. Specifically, they would learn more about hypothesis testing, encoding, how data is split for model training, and more about our selection of Random Forest and why it is suited to our data. Uninformed readers would also learn about the significance of our task of predicting if a dog would be returned to help shelters make better matches for their pets. Additionally, the visualization component of our project will help the reader understand the key features (such as age) that contribute the most to whether or not a dog is returned.

On the other hand, a reader informed both on machine learning and animal shelters may not learn nearly as much as the uninformed reader, but may gain some additional insights from our project. For example, even an informed reader may not know the details on how breed and color variables can impact return rate, but our visualization section helps show that.
